{"id":"2305.08666","submitter":"James Read","authors":"Felipe A. Asenjo and Sergio A. Hojman and Niels Linnemann and James\n  Read","title":"Abnormal light signals and the underdetermination of theory by evidence\n  in astrophysics","comments":"16 pages, 4 figures, critical feedback welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph astro-ph.IM gr-qc","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the propagation of certain non-plane wave solutions to\nMaxwell's equations in both flat and curved spacetimes. We find that the\neffective signal velocity associated to such solutions need not be $c$ and that\nthe signal need not propagate along null geodesics; indeed, more than this, we\nfind that the information encoded in the signals associated with such solutions\ncan be substantially non-local. Having established these results, we then turn\nto their conceptual-philosophical-foundational significance -- which, in brief,\nwe take to be the following: (i) one should not assume that all electromagnetic\nwaves generated in the cosmos are localised plane wave packages; thus, (ii) one\ncannot assume that signals reaching us from the cosmos arrive with a particular\nvelocity (namely, $c$), and that such signals encode local information\nregarding their sources; therefore (iii) astrophysicists and cosmologists\nshould be wary about making such assumptions in their inferences from obtained\ndata -- for to do so may lead to incorrect inferences regarding the nature of\nour universe.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 May 2023 14:17:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-16"}
